); pygidium of females with a shallow longitudinal sulcus; ventrite VI of males with a medial concavity surrounded anterolaterally by carina (
<figureCitation box="[1215,1285,183,205]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–26" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1686,1711]" captionTargetBox="[167,1428,517,1657]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,517,1666]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 24–26. Dasyus male. 24, Dasyus collaris habitus, lateral (without some appendages); 25, D. collaris abdomen, lateroventral; 26, D. variabilis abdomen, lateroventral. Scale = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468203/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="147">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
